    <section id="epidemiological-picture" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Epidemiological Picture</h2>

      <p>The National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES) has consistently found that individuals with higher blood PFAS levels have a significantly increased risk of hypothyroidism. Women with elevated PFAS concentrations show a roughly 36% greater likelihood of thyroid hormone disruption compared to those with lower exposure levels.</p>

      <p>The C8 Health Project — a large epidemiological study of communities in Ohio and West Virginia near a DuPont PFOA-manufacturing facility — produced some of the most detailed human exposure data available. The populations around this facility had PFAS blood concentrations orders of magnitude higher than the general population due to drinking water contamination, and the thyroid disease rates in these communities were correspondingly elevated.</p>

      <p>A 2024 systematic review and meta-analysis found that PFAS exposure may be a risk factor for thyroid cancer, with some studies showing significant positive associations between PFOA exposure and thyroid cancer incidence. The magnitude and consistency of this association across studies varies, but the direction is clear enough to have prompted the Icahn School of Medicine at Mount Sinai's Department of Otolaryngology to include PFAS exposure as a standard question in thyroid cancer patient intake.</p>

      <p>The Michigan PFAS Exposure and Health Study, published in Scientific Reports in 2025, examined 728 adolescents and adults living in a PFAS-contaminated drinking water area. Analyzing 39 individual PFAS compounds against four thyroid hormone measures, researchers found that increasing PFAS concentrations — particularly PFUnA — were associated with decreasing total T3. The mixture analysis confirmed the directional finding: PFAS exposure, at the population level, is suppressing active thyroid hormone.</p>

      <p>The transgenerational data are what make this situation especially grim. PFAS exposure during pregnancy generates alterations that may be passed to children, and in turn to grandchildren, through epigenetic changes that occur in the parental germline. The 2024 review published in <em>Endocrinology, Diabetes &amp; Metabolism</em> characterizes this multi-generational transmission: direct prenatal PFAS exposure during fetal development generates epigenetic marks — DNA methylation changes at thyroid-relevant gene promoters — that alter thyroid axis function in the offspring, independently of whether the child is directly exposed. This is not a hypothetical. It has been demonstrated in animal models, and the epidemiological evidence in human birth cohorts is accumulating.</p>

      <p>The implication is that the PFAS-thyroid damage already accumulated in the population is not bounded by current exposure levels. Even if all PFAS production ceased today — which it has not — the epigenetic legacy of past exposure would continue to shape thyroid function in the children and grandchildren of exposed populations.</p>
    </section>

