    <section id="bpa-phthalates" class="reveal">
      <h2>BPA, Phthalates, and the Broader Endocrine Disruption Landscape</h2>

      <p>Bisphenol A (BPA) is an industrial chemical used in polycarbonate plastics and epoxy resins that line food cans. It is a well-established endocrine disruptor. Its thyroid-specific effects involve multiple mechanisms: BPA can bind to thyroid hormone receptors, acting as either an agonist or antagonist depending on context; it can inhibit T4 binding to transport proteins; and it can interfere with thyroid hormone metabolism.</p>

      <p>A systematic review of human studies found consistent inverse associations between urinary BPA concentrations and thyroid hormone levels, particularly T4, in pregnant women. The same study populations frequently show elevated TSH, consistent with a hypothyroid direction of effect. BPA exposure is particularly concerning during pregnancy, both because the developing fetus is exquisitely sensitive to thyroid hormone levels and because BPA readily crosses the placenta.</p>

      <p>Phthalates — plasticizers found in PVC products, personal care products, food packaging, and pharmaceutical coatings — have documented anti-thyroid effects through multiple pathways including competitive binding to transport proteins and inhibition of deiodinase activity. Several phthalate metabolites have been associated with reduced T4 and T3 levels in epidemiological studies of pregnant women. Like PFAS, phthalates are near-universal in human exposure.</p>

      <p>The challenge is not identifying individual chemicals with thyroid-disrupting effects. The challenge is characterizing the mixture toxicology: humans are not exposed to one thyroid disruptor at a time but to simultaneous low-level exposures to PFAS, perchlorate, fluoride, BPA, phthalates, pesticides, and heavy metals, all of which interact through partially overlapping pathways. The "safe" level of any one of these compounds, established through single-substance dose-response studies, may be a fiction in the real-world context of simultaneous multi-compound exposure. Regulatory frameworks were not designed for mixture toxicology, and they have not been reformed to address it.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="pesticides" class="reveal">
      <h2>Pesticides: The Agricultural Contribution</h2>

      <p>The organophosphate pesticide chlorpyrifos — widely used in American agriculture until the EPA banned its use on food crops in 2021, following nearly two decades of contested regulatory proceedings — is a documented thyroid disruptor. It inhibits thyroid peroxidase activity and has been associated with both elevated TPO antibodies and altered thyroid hormone levels in exposed populations. Its cognitive effects appear to operate, at least in part, through the thyroid pathway: prenatal chlorpyrifos exposure disrupts maternal and fetal thyroid hormone levels at critical neurodevelopmental windows.</p>

      <p>The organochlorine pesticides — compounds like DDT and its metabolite DDE, dioxins, and polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) — were banned in most developed countries decades ago but persist in the environment and in human tissue due to their extreme chemical stability. They continue to show up in thyroid tissue samples, umbilical cord blood, and breast milk. PCBs competitively bind to thyroid hormone transport proteins and can structurally mimic thyroid hormones, binding to thyroid hormone receptors and altering gene expression. Even at the low concentrations present in the general population today, these legacy compounds may be contributing to subclinical thyroid disruption across age cohorts.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="regulatory-failure" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Regulatory Failure</h2>

      <p>The pattern in all of this is not random. It is consistent with a regulatory framework that has been systematically inadequate to the pace and scale of industrial chemical production.</p>

      <p>The Toxic Substances Control Act, which governs chemical safety in the United States, was enacted in 1976 and allowed approximately 62,000 chemicals already in commerce to be grandfathered in without safety testing. The Frank R. Lautenberg Chemical Safety for the 21st Century Act, which reformed TSCA in 2016, improved the framework but retained a presumption of industrial utility and placed the burden of risk demonstration on the EPA rather than on manufacturers. The result is a system where chemicals can be in widespread commercial use — entering drinking water, food packaging, consumer products, and human bodies — for decades before sufficient evidence accumulates for regulatory action, and where, when action is finally taken (as with PFAS), the compounds have already distributed into soil, water, wildlife, and human tissue in ways that no regulatory limit can undo.</p>

      <p>The thyroid specifically has paid a disproportionate price for this framework. It is the organ most sensitive to iodine competition, most responsive to oxidative stress, most susceptible to transport protein displacement, and most consequential in its dysfunction for neurological development. It is, in a sense, the canary in the coal mine for industrial chemical exposure — and the canary has been singing for decades.</p>

      <p>The response has been, to put it charitably, measured.</p>
    </section>

