    <section id="what-people-can-do" class="reveal">
      <h2>What People Can Do</h2>

      <p>This is the section that, in a lesser publication, would consist of actionable tips styled as empowerment. The honest version is more restrained.</p>

      <p>Reducing PFAS exposure involves filtering drinking water through reverse osmosis or activated carbon systems, avoiding non-stick cookware with PTFE coatings, and minimizing consumption of produce known to be grown in PFAS-contaminated soil — a geographic lottery that most people have no practical way to navigate. It involves checking whether one's drinking water source has been contaminated, a process that requires public utility data and map literacy that the majority of the population does not have immediate access to.</p>

      <p>Reducing perchlorate and nitrate exposure involves filtering drinking water and being aware of produce sourced from the American Southwest and from regions using Chilean nitrate fertilizers.</p>

      <p>Reducing BPA and phthalate exposure involves choosing glass, stainless steel, or BPA-free containers — though some BPA-free products have substituted BPS and BPF, chemicals with similar endocrine-disrupting profiles — avoiding canned food where possible, and being aware that "fragrance" in personal care products frequently contains phthalate compounds.</p>

      <p>None of this is comprehensive. All of it is harder for low-income households. And none of it addresses the background PFAS, perchlorate, and organochlorine contamination that is now essentially irreducible in the standard American food supply and water system.</p>

      <p>The appropriate response to this situation is primarily political, not personal. It requires the regulatory overhaul of chemical safety assessment, the funding of mixture toxicology research, the mandatory testing of new chemicals before commercial deployment, and the serious financial liability of industries that have contaminated shared water supplies with chemicals known to impair thyroid function.</p>

      <p>Whether any of that happens at the scale required is not a scientific question. It is a question about whether democratic societies can be organized to protect their endocrine systems from the externalities of an unregulated chemical economy. The answer, historically, has not been encouraging.</p>
    </section>

